==Conquer Cancer Foundation==

Established by the American Society of Clinical Oncology (ASCO), the Conquer Cancer Foundation (formerly the ASCO Cancer Foundation) is a 501(c)(3) charitable organization that supports [[clinical research]] in the field of [[oncology]], patient education, and patient advocacy programs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Conquer Cancer Foundation: Mission, Vision, Case Statement|url=http://www.conquercancerfoundation.org/foundation/Who+We+Are/Our+Story/Foundation+Information/Mission%2C+Vision%2C+Case+Statement|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref>  It funds initiatives spearheaded by the Foundation itself, by ASCO, and by program partners that stand among the most passionate, respected organizations working today in the global campaign against cancer. The Conquer Cancer Foundation's focus extends from [[cancer]] prevention through diagnosis, treatment, end-of-life care, and survivorship.

Since the inception of its Grants and Awards Program in 1984, the Conquer Cancer Foundation has funded more than 800 researchers worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|title=Conquer Cancer Foundation Grants & Awards Program|url=http://www.conquercancerfoundation.org/foundation/Cancer+Professionals/Grants+%26+Awards/Cancer+Research+Map|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref>  The Conquer Cancer Foundation Grants and Awards Program provides funding for a multitude of innovative research initiatives, including the Young Investigator Award, the Career Development Award, and the Merit Award.

